# VSCode Extension & Model Renderer

## Extension (`vscode/src/`)

- Use `vscode-languageclient` for all LSP communication; send custom requests via `client.sendRequest("workspace/executeCommand", { command, arguments })`.
- Keep `extension.ts` thin: just activate, register commands, and call into helpers.
- `webview/panel.ts` owns the `WebviewPanel` lifecycle. Refresh is triggered by three paths: `onDidChangeViewState` (visible), `onDidReceiveMessage` "ready", and `onDidSaveTextDocument`.

## Model renderer (`vscode/model-renderer/src/`)

**State management — Jotai**
- Atoms are the single source of truth. Define them under `store/atoms/` (see `store/atoms/index.ts`).
- The store is created once at module load in `App.tsx` (survives StrictMode remounts).
- Write to atoms from outside React via `store.set()` — used in `services/messageService.ts`.
- Prefer `useAtomValue` (read-only) over `useAtom` unless you need the setter.

**Message service**
- `initMessageService(store)` is called before React renders so the listener and "ready" signal are in place before any message can arrive.
- Message types live in `types/messages.ts`; Rust mirror types in `types/model.ts`.

**Component organisation — styled-components**
- Use `styled-components` for layout and visuals. Keep styled primitives (`styled.div`, `styled.button`, …) in the **same file** as the React components that consume them.
- Group styled definitions in one contiguous block (typically near the top of the file, after imports), separated from logic with a short comment heading — match the existing `// ── Styled components ──` pattern used in `views/` and `components/`.
- Prefer one module per screen or feature; split only when a file grows unwieldy or when styled pieces are reused across several modules (then extract a small shared module and import it).
- App-shell UI (state router, loading/error states) lives in `App.tsx`.
- Each major view has one file in `views/` that owns its private styled primitives and inner helpers (e.g. `InstanceTree.tsx`, `DetailPanel.tsx`).

**Build**
- `npm run build:webview` from `vscode/` (or `npm run build` from `vscode/model-renderer/`) outputs to `out/model-renderer/assets/index.js`.
- After editing the model renderer, rebuild before reloading the extension host.
- The outer `vscode/tsconfig.json` excludes `model-renderer/` — the renderer has its own `tsconfig.app.json`.
